ce:section.ce:para:
Furthermore, with the development of research, extensive attention has been paid to the changes in basic molecular events caused by environmental factors. At present, there are many studies on the toxic molecular mechanism of different nanoparticles on stem cell proliferation and differentiation. First, among all the nonmetallic nanomaterials, carbon nanoparticles on stem cells were found to affect p53 (Al-Hadi et al., 2016), p38 (Yan et al., 2016) and SMAD-dependent bone morphogenetic protein (BMP) signaling pathway (Liu et al., 2010b) in the adipogenic and osteogenic differentiation of mesenchymal stem cells. In many silicon nanoparticles toxicity studies, MAPK and ERK1/2 signaling pathways were activated (Kim et al., 2015a; Carrow et al., 2018), while mTOR dependent signaling pathway was inhibited (Chen et al., 2019), indicating the effect of promoting stem cell proliferation. One study used RNA-Seq to study the effect of silicon dioxide nanoparticles on the proliferation of mouse neural stem cells. From the RNA-Seq results, genes related to apoptosis were significantly changed. The maintenance and proliferation-related signaling pathways, MAPK and PI3K-Akt were also enriched in the pathways affected by silicon dioxide nanoparticles. A core phase II detoxication enzymes gene family, GSTs, was also down-regulated by silicon dioxide nanoparticles in dose-dependent manner (Sun et al., 2017). Another detailed study on the effect of nesosilicates on MSCs for 7 days reported that over 4000 DEGs were found between treated and untreated groups. Clathrin-mediated endocytosis-related gene, CLTCL1 was significantly changed. Moreover, the surface-mediated signaling pathway, such as MAPK/ERK pathway, was activated by nesosilicates. This phenomenon may also promote osteochondral differentiation of hMSCs, which was validated by the direct bone and cartilage lineages differentiation of hMSC(Carrow et al., 2018). In two toxicity studies of new nanomaterials, calcium phosphor cement, we found the influence on the Wnt/β-catenin signaling pathway (Xia et al., 2019), (Liang et al., 2019a), and then on the osteogenic differentiation of mesenchymal stem cells. In the study of the molecular mechanism of the effect of metal nanoparticles on stem cells, we should pay attention to the effect of AgNP. It was found that AgNP could affect the proliferation of stem cells by influencing mitochondrial membrane formation-related genes (Cheung et al., 2016) and NRF2(Oh et al., 2016), MT3 or OSGIN2(Bonaventura et al., 2018) dependent oxidative stress-related signaling pathway. In the differentiation process, it may affect MSCs or ESCs differentiation by affecting AKT/GSK-3/caspase (Repar et al., 2018), GSK-3 A/B, TAU (Begum et al., 2016) and TGFβ(Qin et al., 2014; Zhang et al., 2015) signaling pathway. Many similar conclusions have been found in the study that reported the molecular mechanism of the AuNP effect on stem cells. It was found that AuNP activated MAPK signaling pathway (Yi et al., 2010), (Deng et al., 2016), which influences osteogenic differentiation. Some other studies have found that this effect may be mediated by the WNT pathway (Choi et al., 2015; Liang et al., 2019a). In the study of the nano-sized iron oxide particles on stem cells, it was found that the MAPK pathway signal pathway was activated (Wang et al., 2016b), so that it enhanced osteogenic differentiation of MSCs. When focused on the effects of titanium dioxide particles on stem cells, Yu et al. found that the activation of differentiation and immune stress-related pathways promoted the proliferation of mesenchymal stem cells (Yu et al., 2015). Finally, an RNAseq based method was used to test the development of neural toxicity of cerium oxide nanoparticles (CeO2). Murine and human NSCs were treated with 25 μg/mL CeO2. Axonal guidance signaling pathway, oligodendrocytes and neuroglia formation were significantly changed in human and mouse NSCs. Moreover, some core genes in the neuronal developmental stages were inhibited (Gliga et al., 2017). Quantitative proteomics could also be used to study the mechanisms of nanoparticles on stem cells at the protein level. This technology has been applied in nanotoxicology, and the effects of single-walled carbon nanotubes (Yuan et al., 2011), ZnO NPs(Juang et al., 2014), AgNPs(Verano-Braga et al., 2014) and TiO2(

                           Chen et al., 2018b

                        ) on other cell lines have been detected. Its first application in stem cell nanotoxicology is evaluating the TiO2 effect on hESCs(Pan et al., 2018). Compared with mouse bone marrow-derived macrophages, the proteomic results of the effect on hES cells gave more information about the TiO2 effect on the differentiation process, while the former gave more information about its effect on the metabolic-related pathways. These studies show that proteomics can sensitively reflect the developmental toxicity of nanoparticles. Through proteomics, we could understand the molecular effect of nanomaterials on the metabolism and differentiation potential of stem cells. However, its application in toxicology needs to be further solved due to its high difficulty in operation, high requirements for samples and high sensitivity for mass spectrometry.
